Why: The crew health requirements to perform in-flight microbial monitoring of ISS water, air, and surfaces reside within the ISS Medical Operations Requirements Document (MORD). As such, this monitoring has been performed routinely since the habitation of the first ISS module (
Castro et al.,  2004;
Yamaguchi et al., 2014). The monitoring can be viewed as an assessment of microbial controls that are in place: are the HEPA filters clear and functioning, is the Water Processor Assembly (WPA) performing as designed, and are housekeeping operations being followed? The current monitoring practice relies on the crew collecting samples onto microbial growth media, five days of ambient temperature incubation, and performing a high-level quantification through comparison to a density chart. The slides or culture plates must then be returned to the ground for microbial identification. Following Earth-based analysis, this monitoring strategy provides approximate levels and identities of the cultured microorganisms, which are then used to assess overall risk. This data guides remediation based on both the overall levels as well as the medical significance of the organisms isolated. The ISS microbial monitoring practice has resulted in an overall healthy vehicle and crew, but the significant limitation is the requirement of sample return. Additionally, the reliance on culture produces both a bias to those organisms that can be cultured and a substantial delay between sample collection and analytical results. It is critical to establish and validate a means of near real-time environmental and human health diagnostics for exploration missions.
